data.content:
Here are the three breaking changes in EF Core 10 and their fixes:

## 1. `SetProperty` value parameter now requires a lambda expression

In EF Core 10, `SetProperty`'s value parameter changed from `TProperty` to `Expression<Func<TSource, TProperty>>`. Your manual expression tree passes `Expression.Constant("foo")` directly — it now needs to be wrapped in a lambda:

```csharp
// Before (EF Core 9): value was a bare expression
arguments: new Expression[]
{
    Expression.Lambda<Func<Blog, string>>(
        Expression.Property(blogParameter, nameof(Blog.Name)), blogParameter),
    Expression.Constant("foo")  // ❌ no longer valid
}

// After (EF Core 10): value must be a lambda expression
var valueParameter = Expression.Parameter(typeof(Blog), "b2");
arguments: new Expression[]
{
    Expression.Lambda<Func<Blog, string>>(
        Expression.Property(blogParameter, nameof(Blog.Name)), blogParameter),
    Expression.Lambda<Func<Blog, string>>(       // ✅ wrap in lambda
        Expression.Constant("foo"), valueParameter)
}
```

Also update the initial seed setter:
```csharp
Expression<Func<SetPropertyCalls<Blog>, SetPropertyCalls<Blog>>> setters =
    s => s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, b => 8);  // note: b => 8
```

## 2. Complex types: duplicate CLR types require explicit column prefixes

EF Core 10 no longer auto-disambiguates complex properties that share the same CLR type. You must explicitly configure column prefixes:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, ab => {
        ab.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
        // ... other properties
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ab => {
        ab.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested: use explicit column naming at each level
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, pb => {
        pb.ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress, ab => {
            ab.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("Payment_BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` gained a `CommandSource` parameter

EF Core 10 added `CommandSource commandSource` to the diagnostics methods:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        CommandSource commandSource)   // ✅ new parameter
    { /* logging */ }
}
```

The `CommandSource` enum tells you whether the command originated from `SaveChanges`, `LinqQuery`, `ExecuteUpdate`, `Migrations`, etc. — useful for filtering your log output.
